00:55:13.950 --> 00:55:16.620
with a lot of
resources, or is it

00:55:16.620 --> 00:55:18.420
applicable to small
companies as well?"

00:55:18.420 --> 00:55:20.550
So Pete, do you want to
take a stab, or you want--

00:55:20.550 --> 00:55:21.400
PETER FADER: Go for it first.

00:55:21.400 --> 00:55:22.025
SARAH TOMS: OK.

00:55:22.025 --> 00:55:23.460
All right.

00:55:23.460 --> 00:55:27.480
So what we think here is that
these are universal principles,

00:55:27.480 --> 00:55:28.860
for sure.

00:55:28.860 --> 00:55:32.100
When you're thinking
about your customers,

00:55:32.100 --> 00:55:34.290
it's also-- one thing you
have to be worried about

00:55:34.290 --> 00:55:35.940
is the over-investment, right?

00:55:35.940 --> 00:55:38.940
So if you're over-investing in
customers that really aren't

00:55:38.940 --> 00:55:41.910
worth it, that's something that
will happen to you regardless

00:55:41.910 --> 00:55:43.544
of the size of your company.

00:55:43.544 --> 00:55:45.210
The other thing that
we work really hard

00:55:45.210 --> 00:55:47.040
at in the book-- in
fact we've structured

00:55:47.040 --> 00:55:49.081
the book in such a way
that we're talking-- we're

00:55:49.081 --> 00:55:52.350
trying to train your eye to
look at acquisition, retention,

00:55:52.350 --> 00:55:55.940
development, and
then understand time.

00:55:55.940 --> 00:55:57.840
There's a time
component to that--

00:55:57.840 --> 00:55:59.800
where you are in the
maturity of your company,

00:55:59.800 --> 00:56:01.560
whether you're large
or small, and how

00:56:01.560 --> 00:56:03.130
that changes your tactics.

00:56:03.130 --> 00:56:04.860
We're talking
about being nimble,

00:56:04.860 --> 00:56:06.840
about experimenting
like I said before,

00:56:06.840 --> 00:56:08.850
about testing your hypotheses.

00:56:08.850 --> 00:56:10.530
And these are
principles, especially

00:56:10.530 --> 00:56:13.140
in the era of data
that we're in,

00:56:13.140 --> 00:56:15.362
that are applicable whether
you're large or small.

00:56:15.362 --> 00:56:17.820
PETER FADER: And let me just
add to that, because in an era

00:56:17.820 --> 00:56:21.150
where everyday we're talking
about the retail apocalypse

00:56:21.150 --> 00:56:23.790
and all this kind of thing, I'm
actually very hopeful about it.

00:56:23.790 --> 00:56:27.250
And I think that the future
rises from the small companies.

00:56:27.250 --> 00:56:29.980
Those digitally-native,
direct-to-consumer companies,

00:56:29.980 --> 00:56:33.540
many of which are
right around here--

00:56:33.540 --> 00:56:36.750
I don't want to say that they're
textbook customer centricity

00:56:36.750 --> 00:56:37.457
examples.

00:56:37.457 --> 00:56:39.790
But they're are a heck of a
lot better than their older,

00:56:39.790 --> 00:56:41.670
bigger, slower brethren.

00:56:41.670 --> 00:56:44.310
And so again, implicitly
or explicitly,

00:56:44.310 --> 00:56:46.380
they're starting to embrace
a lot of these ideas.

00:56:46.380 --> 00:56:49.020
They're starting to tag and
track customers, calculate CLVs

00:56:49.020 --> 00:56:51.810
a lot earlier than
traditional companies would.

00:56:51.810 --> 00:56:53.992
And what's happening is
those big old companies

00:56:53.992 --> 00:56:55.950
are starting to take them
a lot more seriously.

00:56:55.950 --> 00:56:58.560
Instead of dismissing them as
a passing fad or just a little

00:56:58.560 --> 00:57:00.052
teeny tiny niche,
they're saying,

00:57:00.052 --> 00:57:01.260
we can learn a lot from them.

00:57:01.260 --> 00:57:01.950
You know what?

00:57:01.950 --> 00:57:05.010
Let's hire some of them to
start running our marketing

00:57:05.010 --> 00:57:06.430
or our whole company.

00:57:06.430 --> 00:57:08.250
So I think a lot
of these ideas are

00:57:08.250 --> 00:57:10.120
kind of working their way up.

00:57:10.120 --> 00:57:14.101
And sometimes it's the little
companies leading the way.

00:57:14.101 --> 00:57:14.600
Rodney.

00:57:14.600 --> 00:57:15.391
AUDIENCE: Hey, hey.

00:57:15.391 --> 00:57:16.050
Hi.

00:57:16.050 --> 00:57:19.030
Thank you guys both for today.

00:57:19.030 --> 00:57:21.780
Kind of related to
that last point--

00:57:21.780 --> 00:57:23.730
is there a certain threshold--

00:57:23.730 --> 00:57:25.210
not so much size of company--

00:57:25.210 --> 00:57:28.110
but maybe threshold
of data that you need?

00:57:28.110 --> 00:57:33.420
So for instance, do you need
5,000 customers or 5 million?

00:57:33.420 --> 00:57:35.140
Do you need two
years, three years,

00:57:35.140 --> 00:57:36.870
or five years of
transaction data

00:57:36.870 --> 00:57:38.820
to actually make
that model work?

00:57:38.820 --> 00:57:39.840
What's the thresholds?

00:57:39.840 --> 00:57:41.625
Because that will
definitely tell us.

00:57:41.625 --> 00:57:43.740
It may be a small company
growing very rapidly.

00:57:43.740 --> 00:57:46.500
But then you hit a certain
threshold of customers,

00:57:46.500 --> 00:57:48.720
but you don't have enough
years or enough data

00:57:48.720 --> 00:57:50.190
to actually make the model work.

00:57:50.190 --> 00:57:51.321
Any thoughts or comments?

00:57:51.321 --> 00:57:52.320
PETER FADER: Absolutely.

00:57:52.320 --> 00:57:54.805
I sort of almost implicitly
answered the question

00:57:54.805 --> 00:57:56.830
when I was talking about
the kinds of companies

00:57:56.830 --> 00:57:58.420
that we work with on
customer-based corporate

00:57:58.420 --> 00:57:58.920
valuation.

00:57:58.920 --> 00:58:00.940
I said, late-stage VCs.

00:58:00.940 --> 00:58:03.010
You can't really do it
at the early stages,

00:58:03.010 --> 00:58:05.050
for exactly the reasons
you pointed out,

00:58:05.050 --> 00:58:07.000
that you don't have
enough customers to really

00:58:07.000 --> 00:58:10.240
see or estimate that
full CLV distribution.

00:58:10.240 --> 00:58:12.820
And in terms of the length
of the runway that you need,

00:58:12.820 --> 00:58:14.620
it's kind of
interesting that I don't

00:58:14.620 --> 00:58:16.570
need a long runway of data.

00:58:16.570 --> 00:58:17.810
I need enough customers.

00:58:17.810 --> 00:58:19.510
But I don't need a
long amount of time

00:58:19.510 --> 00:58:21.020
in order to estimate
these models.

00:58:21.020 --> 00:58:23.170
But I still don't
really trust them

00:58:23.170 --> 00:58:25.250
until I have about
two or three years.

00:58:25.250 --> 00:58:26.710
And why is that?

00:58:26.710 --> 00:58:29.162
Because one of the issues
that we haven't spoken about--

00:58:29.162 --> 00:58:30.870
but we make a big deal
about in the book,

00:58:30.870 --> 00:58:32.745
and I can't say enough
about it in practice--

00:58:32.745 --> 00:58:34.390
are cohorts of customers.

00:58:34.390 --> 00:58:37.900
We always run these models for
a given group of customers,

00:58:37.900 --> 00:58:40.090
generally who we acquired
at the same time.

00:58:40.090 --> 00:58:42.880
And the issue is that the
cohorts are not all created

00:58:42.880 --> 00:58:44.766
equal, and that as
we go over time--

00:58:44.766 --> 00:58:47.140
so we get that first cohort
of customers we acquired soon

00:58:47.140 --> 00:58:48.370
after we were founded--

00:58:48.370 --> 00:58:50.870
they tend to be much
better customers.

00:58:50.870 --> 00:58:53.440
And so we don't want to just
calculate CLVs on them and say,

00:58:53.440 --> 00:58:55.150
we're an amazing company.

00:58:55.150 --> 00:58:56.920
Let's raise some more capital.

00:58:56.920 --> 00:59:01.270
So we need enough time to see a
bunch of the different cohorts.

00:59:01.270 --> 00:59:03.910
We have to play connect
the dots across them.

00:59:03.910 --> 00:59:06.670
We've got to watch them start
to stabilize a little bit,

00:59:06.670 --> 00:59:08.800
so we can anticipate
what the subsequent

00:59:08.800 --> 00:59:12.022
and the steady state, mature
cohorts are going to look like.

00:59:12.022 --> 00:59:13.480
So yes, we do need
enough customers

00:59:13.480 --> 00:59:14.950
to see the heterogeneity.

00:59:14.950 --> 00:59:18.610
We do need enough of a runway to
see the cross-cohort dynamics.

00:59:18.610 --> 00:59:21.910
And obviously, we do need
enough cleanliness of data

00:59:21.910 --> 00:59:24.140
to trust those results
in the first place.

00:59:24.140 --> 00:59:27.040
Sometimes these models
that I endorse--

00:59:27.040 --> 00:59:29.140
sometimes they're too
good, that they'll

00:59:29.140 --> 00:59:31.870
work really well even when
you put in crappy data.

00:59:31.870 --> 00:59:34.750
And it gives you this false
sense of security about it.

00:59:34.750 --> 00:59:38.164
So all the issues you raised
are right on the money.

00:59:38.164 --> 00:59:39.580
And with that in
mind, I recognize

00:59:39.580 --> 00:59:43.000
that most companies aren't born
to do customer centricity right

00:59:43.000 --> 00:59:43.890
out of the gate.

00:59:43.890 --> 00:59:46.490
They're going to be born
around a particular product.

00:59:46.490 --> 00:59:49.120
We just want them to
look ahead and start

00:59:49.120 --> 00:59:50.620
doing all that
tagging and tracking,

00:59:50.620 --> 00:59:52.810
because two, three years
later, maybe it's time

00:59:52.810 --> 00:59:54.470
to do that pivot towards it.

00:59:54.470 --> 00:59:55.990
But it's going to
take some time.

